snippet.textDisplay: No offence Dustin, but you guys shouldn’t play like this. Spinning machines are no joke and not only you had zero protection (your school yard is nowhere near safe), but also stuff like that should be calculated by a mechanical engineer. Not only your bat failed unexpectedly, your bearing broke unexpectedly as you certainly didn’t calculate the dynamic forces, your rotor support is a freaking wooden table shaking, many times too light, no suspension, no rigid foundation... Please get some opinion from a mechanical engineer next time for your own safety.

snippet.textDisplay: ADVICE: Of course the bat breaks. It's rigidly attached, and as you said yourself, you will get a tremendous force-concentration at the junction. Instead, you should make a bendable attachment, like a thick piece of rubber from a tyre or such. Just look at how a rotor blade of a helicopter is attached, it can always swing back and forth relative to the hub. It will stay in the radial position due to centripetal force anyway.
snippet.textOriginal: ADVICE: Of course the bat breaks. It's rigidly attached, and as you said yourself, you will get a tremendous force-concentration at the junction. Instead, you should make a bendable attachment, like a thick piece of rubber from a tyre or such. Just look at how a rotor blade of a helicopter is attached, it can always swing back and forth relative to the hub. It will stay in the radial position due to centripetal force anyway.
